fb.text: I was horrified to be told today by a member of Logan City Council that they were not attending to "wandering dog" help calls because "we\'re full". I was asked if the dog was dangerous. Hang on, let me go approach it and see if it bites me. Or better yet, let\'s take my small child I\'m walking with near the dog and test it out. I am not an animal management professional. I expect myself and my family to be protected from escaped animals. Even a "nice" dog can wander onto the road causing a major traffic accident. If there is no room for these dogs to be held while finding their owners I assume the council is working hard on finding a solution to this problem. But simply saying "no, no room, we\'re not coming" is completely unacceptable and dangerous.

Our next Household Paint and Chemical Drop Off Day is Saturday 5 May 2018, 8am to 4pm at the Greenbank and Beenleigh Waste and Recycling Facilities.

Residents will be entitled to bring up to 10 litres of each of the following chemical types:Water based paints, Solvent and water based paints, Pesticides, Arsenic based materials, Photographic solutions, Pharmaceuticals, Acids, Alkalis, Solvents, Pool chlorine and Petrol. Materials that do not fall into the above categories will not be accepted.

Please note that Council will be retaining all the containers that paint and chemicals are presented in.

Materials such as fluorescent tubes, cooking oil, vehicle batteries, domestic smoke detectors, rechargeable batteries, mobile phones and accessories, sharps (used syringes - residents only) and tyres are accepted at the landfill 365 days per year. There is no charge for disposal of these materials with the exception of motor oil ($0.30 per litre for every litre in excess of 25 litres) and tyres (ranging from $4.00 for car tyres).

For more information, visit https://bit.ly/1NEgOS8

It’s time to celebrate! \U0001f38a\U0001f389

This month’s Eats & Beats is the 30 year celebration of the opening of the Kingston Butter Factory Community Arts Centre and to celebrate we are:

• Opening up the venue with Devonshire tea and scones \U0001f370☕
• the Art Cooperative and the Historical Museum will all be open to celebrate \U0001f3a8\U0001f5bc️

Come along and celebrate the 30 year anniversary with some delicious food and dance the night away! \U0001f38a\U0001f389

For more info on this month's Eats & Beats head to: https://goo.gl/neyJHu
---------------

**Some history about the Kingston Butter Factory**

The Southern Queensland Co-operative Dairy Association Factory commenced making butter in May 1907. The original timber building was reclad in brick and modernised in 1932 and remains much in this form today.

The dairy company Peters took over in 1958 into producing milk and cottage cheese, but all production ceased in April 1983. The building was acquired by Logan City Council in 1986 and redeveloped the Kingston Butter Factory Community Arts Centre as a Bicentennial project the following utilising funding from all three levels of government.

It officially opened with a concert in the Butter Box Theatre on 27 February 1988.", u'story': u'Logan City Council shared a post.
